answers.body_markdown:
    Vector&lt;int&gt; v(CustomAllocator&lt;int&gt;());

You got hit by the [most vexing parse](https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Most_vexing_parse).  `Vector&lt;int&gt; v(CustomAllocator&lt;int&gt;());` can be parsed as a variable declaration _or_ a function declaration and the grammar prefers the latter. Therefore, the compiler thinks that `v` is a function and this it why you get the &quot;expression must have class type&quot; error -- you can only invoke methods on values with a class type, but `v` is a function.

Even if you fixed that error using one of these options:

    // C++03 solution (extra parens)
    Vector&lt;int&gt; v((CustomAllocator&lt;int&gt;()));

    // C++11 solution (uniform initialization)
    Vector&lt;int&gt; v{CustomAllocator&lt;int&gt;{}};

Your code still wouldn&#39;t do what you expected, _though it would run._  `Vector&lt;int&gt;` is the same thing as `Vector&lt;int, std::allocator&gt;` and so `v` will still use the standard allocator.

Why doesn&#39;t this cause a compilation error?  Because `CustomAllocator&lt;int&gt;` _inherits_ `std::allocator&lt;int&gt;` (which it shouldn&#39;t!), so the `std::allocator&lt;int&gt;` copy constructor is used to slice your custom allocator into an `std::allocator&lt;int&gt;` and then the program proceeds using the standard allocator.  Your `CustomAllocator&lt;int&gt;` temporary is basically converted into an `std::allocator&lt;int&gt;`.

To illustrate, both of the above &quot;fixed&quot; examples are _roughly_ equivalent to this code (if we disregard some value copies/moves that are irrelevant to the program&#39;s observable behavior):

    // Creates a custom allocator value.
    CustomAllocator&lt;int&gt; a;

    // Custom allocator is converted to std::allocator&lt;int&gt;.
    std::allocator&lt;int&gt; b(a);

    // std::allocator&lt;int&gt; is provided to the Vector constructor.
    Vector&lt;int&gt; v(b);

The correct fix is to specify the second `Vector` type parameter and then the constructor arguments aren&#39;t even needed since the default constructor will do the right thing:

    Vector&lt;int, CustomAllocator&gt; v;

